According to a University of Chicago study, the first few years of a man’s divorce usually involve anger, rationalizing and attempts to justify the split, denial, and then finally loss and grief. Men feel a tremendous amount of shame about their failed marriage, and they may lash out during this stage by belittling the other person and even attacking the custodial times with their children, something that hurts them much more than they will ever admit.

What can you expect to see as part of the grieving process for men when they lose their marriage to divorce? Many men will enter into a self-destructive period where they do things like abuse drugs or alcohol, eat too much, or gain weight. In other cases, they may go in the opposite direction and go on an extreme fitness and diet regimen to try to rebalance themselves. Eventually, most men will enter a period of action and recovery until eventually they establish a more stable pattern that allows them to plan their future. This process is something that takes a man a long time to complete, often several years.

What Does Recovery Look Like for a Man After Divorce?
